# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hart-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] In electrical signalling an analog **current loop** is used where a device must be monitored or controlled remotely over a pair of conductors.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Only one current level can be present at any time.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] They are also used to transmit controller outputs to the modulating field devices such as control valves.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] These loops have the advantages of simplicity and noise immunity, and have a large international user and equipment supplier base.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Some 4–20 mA field devices can be powered by the current loop itself, removing the need for separate power supplies, and the "smart" Highway Addressable Remote Transducer (HART) Protocol uses the loop for communications between field devices and controllers.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Various automation protocols may replace analog current loops, but 4–20 mA is still a principal industrial standard.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] In industrial process control, analog 4–20 mA current loops are commonly used for electronic signalling, with the two values of 4 and 20 mA representing 0–100% of the range of measurement or control.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] These loops are used both for carrying sensor information from field instrumentation and carrying control signals to the process modulating devices, such as a valve.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Field instrumentation measurements include pressure, temperature, level, flow, pH or other process variables.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] A current loop can also be used to control a valve positioner or other output actuator.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Since input terminals of instruments may have one side of the current loop input tied to the chassis ground (earth), analog isolators may be required when connecting several instruments in series.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] The relationship between current value and process variable measurement is set by calibration, which assigns different ranges of engineering units to the span between 4 and 20 mA.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] The mapping between engineering units and current can be inverted, so that 4 mA represents the maximum and 20 mA the minimum.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Depending on the source of current for the loop, devices may be classified as *active* (supplying or "sourcing" power) or *passive* (relying on or "sinking" loop power).
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] For example, a chart recorder may provide loop power to a pressure transmitter.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] The pressure transmitter modulates the current on the loop to send the signal to the strip chart recorder, but does not in itself supply power to the loop and so is passive.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Another loop may contain two passive chart recorders, a passive pressure transmitter, and a 24 V battery (the battery is the active device).
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Note that a *4-wire* instrument has a power-supply input separate from the current loop.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Panel mount displays and chart recorders are commonly termed "indicator devices" or "process monitors".
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Several passive indicator devices may be connected in series, but a loop must have only one transmitter device and only one power source (active device).
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] The 4–20 mA convention was born in the 1950s out of the earlier highly successful 3–15 psi pneumatic control signal standard, when electronics became cheap and reliable enough to emulate the older standard electrically.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] The 3–15 psi standard had the same features of being able to power some remote devices, and have a "live" zero.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] However, the 4–20 mA standard was better suited to the electronic controllers being developed at the time.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] The transition was gradual and has extended into the 21st century, due to the huge installed base of 3–15 psi devices.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] As the operation of pneumatic valves over motorised valves has many cost and reliability advantages, pneumatic actuation is still an industry standard.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] To allow the construction of hybrid systems, where the 4–20 mA is generated by the controller, but allows the use of pneumatic valves, a range of current to pressure (I to P) converters are available from manufacturers.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] These are usually local to the control valve and convert 4–20 mA to 3–15 psi (or 0.2–1.0 bar).
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] This signal is then fed to the valve actuator or, more commonly, a pneumatic positioner.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] The positioner is a dedicated controller which has a mechanical linkage to the actuator movement.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] This ensures that problems of friction are overcome and the valve control element moves to the desired position.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] It also allows the use of higher air pressures for valve actuation.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] With the development of cheap industrial micro-processors, "smart" valve positioners have become available since the mid-1980s and are very popular for new installations.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] These include an I to P converter, plus valve position and condition monitoring.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] These latter are fed back over the current loop to the controller, using protocols such as HART.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Analogue current loops were historically occasionally carried between buildings by dry pairs in telephone cables leased from the local telephone company.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] 4–20 mA loops were more common in the days of analog telephony.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] These circuits require end-to-end direct current (DC) continuity, and unless a dedicated wire pair was hardwired, their use ceased with the introduction of semiconductor switching.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] DC continuity is not available over a microwave radio, optical fibre, or a multiplexed telephone circuit connection.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Basic DC circuit theory shows that the current is the same all along the line.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] It was common to see 4–20 mA circuits that had loop lengths in miles or circuits working over telephone cable pairs that were longer than ten thousand feet end-to-end.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] There are still legacy systems in place using this technology.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] In Bell System circuits, voltages up to 125 V DC were employed.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Discrete control functions can be represented by discrete levels of current sent over a loop.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] This would allow multiple control functions to be operated over a single pair of wires.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Currents required for a specific function vary from one application or manufacturer to another.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] There is no specific current that is tied to a single meaning.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] It is almost universal that 0 mA indicates the circuit has failed.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] In the case of a fire alarm, 6 mA could be normal, 15 mA could mean a fire has been detected, and 0 mA would produce a trouble indication, telling the monitoring site the alarm circuit had failed.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Some devices, such as two-way radio remote control consoles, can reverse the polarity of currents and can multiplex audio onto a DC current.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] These devices can be employed for any remote control need a designer might imagine.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] For example, a current loop could actuate an evacuation siren or command synchronized traffic signals.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Current loop circuits are one possible way used to control radio base stations at distant sites.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] The two-way radio industry calls this type of remote control **DC remote**.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] This name comes from the need for DC circuit continuity between the control point and the radio base station.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] A current loop remote control saves the cost of extra pairs of wires between the operating point and the radio transceiver.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Some equipment, such as the Motorola MSF-5000 base station, uses currents below 4 mA for some functions.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] An alternative type, the tone remote, is more complex but requires only an audio path between control point and base station.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] For example, a taxi dispatch base station might be physically located on the rooftop of an eight-story building.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] The taxi company office might be in the basement of a different building nearby.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] The office would have a remote control unit that would operate the taxi company base station over a current loop circuit.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] The circuit would normally be over a telephone line or similar wiring.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Control function currents come from the remote control console at the dispatch office end of a circuit.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] In two-way radio use, an idle circuit would normally have no current present.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] In two-way radio use, radio manufacturers use different currents for specific functions.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Polarities are changed to get more possible functions over a single circuit.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] If a telephone company cable splicer accidentally reversed the conductors, selecting channel 2 would lock the transmitter on.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Each current level could close a set of contacts, or operate solid-state logic, at the other end of the circuit.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] That contact closure caused a change of state on the controlled device.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] Some remote control equipment could have options set to allow compatibility between manufacturers.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] That is, a base station that was configured to transmit with a +18 mA current could have options changed to (instead) make it transmit when +6 mA was present.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] In two-way radio use, AC signals were also present on the circuit pair.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] If the base station were idle, receive audio would be sent over the line from the base station to the dispatch office.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] In the presence of a transmit command current, the remote control console would send audio to be transmitted.
[src:hart-protocol/4-20-ma] The voice of the user in the dispatch office would be modulated and superimposed over the DC current that caused the transmitter to operate.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] A **fieldbus** is a member of a family of industrial digital communication networks used for real-time distributed control.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Fieldbus profiles are standardized by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) as IEC 61784/61158.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] A complex automated industrial system is typically structured in hierarchical levels as a distributed control system (DCS).
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In this hierarchy the upper levels for production managements are linked to the direct control level of programmable logic controllers (PLC) via a non-time-critical communications system (e.g.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The fieldbus links the PLCs of the direct control level to the components in the plant at the field level, such as sensors, actuators, electric motors, console lights, switches, valves and contactors.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] It also replaces the direct connections via current loops or digital I/O signals.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The requirements for a fieldbus are therefore time-critical and cost-sensitive.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Since the new millennium, a number of fieldbuses based on Real-time Ethernet have been established.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] These have the potential to replace traditional fieldbuses in the long term.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] A fieldbus is an industrial network system for real-time distributed control.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] It is a way to connect instruments in a manufacturing plant.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] A fieldbus works on a network structure which typically allows daisy-chain, star, ring, branch, and tree network topologies.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Previously, computers were connected using RS-232 (serial connections) by which only two devices could communicate.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] This reduces both the length of and total number of cables required.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Furthermore, since devices that communicate through a fieldbus require a microprocessor, multiple points are typically provided by the same device.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Some fieldbus devices now support control schemes such as PID control on the device-side instead of forcing the controller to do the processing.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The most important motivation to use a fieldbus in a distributed control system is to reduce the cost for installation and maintenance of the installation without losing the high availability and reliability of the automation system.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The goal is to use a two wire cable and simple configuration for field devices from different manufacturers.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Depending on the application, the number of sensors and actuators vary from hundreds in one machine up to several thousands distributed over a large plant.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The history of the fieldbus demonstrates how these goals have been approached over time.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Arguably the precursor field bus technology is HP-IB as described in IEEE 488 in 1975.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] "It became known as the General Purpose Interface Bus (GPIB), and became a de facto standard for automated and industrial instrument control".
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The GPIB has its main application in automated measurements with instruments from different manufacturers.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] It is a parallel bus with a cable and connector with 24 wires, limited to a maximal cable length of 20 metres.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The oldest commonly used field bus technology is Bitbus.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Bitbus was created by Intel Corporation to enhance use of Multibus systems in industrial systems by separating slow i/o functions from faster memory access.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In 1983, Intel created the 8044 Bitbus microcontroller by adding field bus firmware to its existing 8051 microcontroller.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Bitbus uses EIA-485 at the physical layer, with two twisted pairs - one for data and the other for clocking and signals.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Use of SDLC at the data link layer permits 250 nodes on one segment with a total distance of 13.2 km.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Bitbus has one master node and multiple slaves, with slaves only responding to requests from the master.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Bitbus does not define routing at the network layer.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The 8044 permits only a relatively small data packet (13 bytes), but embeds an efficient set of RAC (remote access and control) tasks and the ability to develop custom RAC tasks.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In 1990, the IEEE adopted Bitbus as the Microcontroller System Serial Control Bus (IEEE-1118).
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Today BITBUS is maintained by the BEUG - BITBUS European Users Group.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Office networks are not really suited for automation applications, as they lack the upper-bounded transmission delay.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] ARCNET, which was conceived as early as 1975 for office connectivity uses a token mechanism and therefore found later uses in industry.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Automation Protocol (MAP) was an implementation of OSI-compliant protocols in automation technology initiated by General Motors in 1984.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] MAP became a LAN standardization proposal supported by many manufacturers and was mainly used in factory automation.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] MAP used the 10 Mbit/s IEEE 802.4 token bus as a transmission medium.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Due to its scope and complexity, MAP failed to make a big breakthrough.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] To reduce the complexity and reach faster processing with reduced resources the Enhanced Performance Architecture (EPA) MAP was developed in 1988.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] This MiniMap contains only levels 1, 2, and 7 of the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) basic reference model.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] This shortcut was taken over by later fieldbus definitions.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The most important achievement of MAP is Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS), the application layer of MAP.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS) is an international standard ISO 9506 dealing with an application protocol and services for transferring real time process data and supervisory control information between networked devices or computer applications published as a first version in 1986.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] It has been a model for many further developments in other industrial communication standardizations such as FMS for Profibus or SDO for CANopen.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] It is still in use as a possible application layer e.g. for power utility automation in the IEC 61850 standards.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In the field of manufacturing automation the requirements for a fieldbus are to support short reaction times with only a few bits or bytes to be transmitted over not more than some hundreds of meters.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In 1979 Modicon (now Schneider Electric) defined a serial bus to connect their programmable logic controllers (PLCs) called Modbus.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In its first version Modbus used a two wire cable with EIA 485 UART signals.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The protocol itself is very simple with a master/slave protocol and the number of data types are limited to those understood by PLCs at the time.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Nevertheless, Modbus is (with its Modbus-TCP version) still one of the most used industrial networks, mainly in the building automation field.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] A research project with the financial support of the German government defined in 1987 the fieldbus PROFIBUS based on the *Fieldbus Message Specification* (FMS).
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In practical applications, it proved too complicated to handle in the field.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In 1994 Siemens proposed a modified application layer with the name *Decentralized Periphery* (DP) which reached a good acceptance in the manufacturing industry.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] As of 2016, the Profibus is one of the most installed fieldbuses in the world and reached 60 million installed nodes in 2018.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In 1987 Phoenix Contact developed a serial bus to connect spatially distributed inputs and outputs to a centralized controller.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The controller sends one frame over a physical ring, which contains all input and output data.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The cable has 5 wires: besides the ground signal, two wires for the outgoing frame and two wires for the returning frame.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] With this cable is it possible to have the whole installation in a tree topology.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The INTERBUS was very successful in the manufacturing industry with more than 22,9 million devices installed in the field.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The Interbus joined the Profinet technology for Ethernet-based fieldbus Profinet and the INTERBUS is now maintained by the Profibus Nutzerorganisation e.V.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] During the 1980s, to solve communication problems between different control systems in cars, the German company Robert Bosch GmbH first developed the Controller Area Network (CAN).
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The concept of CAN was that every device can be connected by a single set of wires, and every device that is connected can freely exchange data with any other device.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] CAN soon migrated into the factory automation marketplace (with many others).
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In process automation traditionally most of the field transmitters are connected over a current loop with 4-20 mA to the controlling device.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] This allows not only to transmit the measured value with the level of the current, but also provide the required electrical power to the field device with just one two-wire cable of a length of more than a thousand meters.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] These systems are also installed in hazardous areas.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] According to NAMUR a fieldbus in these applications has to fulfill these requirements.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] A special standard for instrumentation, IEC/EN 60079-27, describes requirements for the Fieldbus Intrinsically Safe Concept (FISCO) for installations in zone 0, 1 or 2.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The FIP standard is based on a French initiative in 1982 to create a requirements analysis for a future field bus standard.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The study led to the European Eureka initiative for a field bus standard in June 1986 that included 13 partners.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The development group (réseaux locaux industriels) created the first proposal to be standardized in France.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The name of the FIP field bus was originally given as an abbreviation of the French "Flux d'Information vers le Processus" while later referring to FIP with the English name "Factory Instrumentation Protocol".
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] FIP has lost ground to Profibus which came to prevail the market in Europe in the following decade - the WorldFIP homepage has seen no press release since 2002.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The closest cousin of the FIP family can be found today in the Wire Train Bus for train coaches.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] However a specific subset of WorldFIP - known the FIPIO protocol - can be found widely in machine components.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus was developed over a period of many years by the International Society of Automation (ISA) as SP50.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus today enjoys a growing installed base in many heavy process applications such as refining, petrochemicals, power generation, and even food and beverage, pharmaceuticals, and nuclear applications.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Effective January 1, 2015, the Fieldbus Foundation has become part of the new FieldComm Group.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Profibus PA (process automation) is used for communication between measuring and process instruments, actuators and process control system or PLC/DCS in process engineering.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Profibus PA is a Profibus version with physical layer suitable for process automation, in which several segments (PA segments) with field instruments can be connected to Profibus DP via so-called couplers.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The two-wire bus cable of these segments takes over not only the communication, but also the power supply of the participants (MBP transmission technology).
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Another special feature of Profibus PA is the widely used device profile "PA Devices" (PA Profile), in which the most important functions of the field devices are standardized across manufacturers.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The BatiBUS defined in 1989 and used mainly in France, the Instabus extended to the European Installation Bus (EIB) and the European Home Systems Protocol (EHS) merged in 1999 to the Konnex) (KNX) standard EN 50090, (ISO/IEC 14543-3).
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In 2020 495 Member companies offer 8'000 products with KNX interfaces in 190 countries worldwide.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Going back to the 1980s, unlike other networks, LonWorks is the result of the work of computer scientists from Echelon Corporation.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In 1999 the communications protocol (then known as LonTalk) was submitted to ANSI and accepted as a standard for control networking (ANSI/CEA-709.1-B), in 2005 as EN 14908 (European building automation standard).
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The protocol is also one of several data link/physical layers of the BACnet ASHRAE/ANSI standard for building automation.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The BACnet standard was initially developed and is now maintained by the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE) starting in 1987.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] BACnet is an American National Standard (ANSI) 135 since 1995, a European standard, a national standard in many countries, and global ISO Standard 16484 since 2003.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] BACnet has in 2017 a market share of 60% in building automation market.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Although fieldbus technology has been around since 1988, with the completion of the ISA S50.02 standard, the development of the international standard took many years.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In 1999, the IEC SC65C/WG6 standards committee met to resolve difference in the draft IEC fieldbus standard.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The result of this meeting was the initial form of the IEC 61158 standard with eight different protocol sets called "Types".
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] This form of standard was first developed for the European Common Market, concentrates less on commonality, and achieves its primary purpose—elimination of restraint of trade between nations.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Issues of commonality are now left to the international consortia that support each of the fieldbus standard types.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Almost as soon as it was approved, the IEC standards development work ceased and the committee was dissolved.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] A new IEC committee SC65C/MT-9 was formed to resolve the conflicts in form and substance within the more than 4000 pages of IEC 61158.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The work on the above protocol types is substantially complete.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] New protocols, such as for safety fieldbuses or real-time Ethernet fieldbuses are being accepted into the definition of the international fieldbus standard during a typical 5-year maintenance cycle.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In the 2008 version of the standard, the fieldbus types are reorganized into Communication Profile Families (CPFs).
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] There were many competing technologies for fieldbuses and the original hope for one single unified communications mechanism has not been realized.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] This should not be unexpected since fieldbus technology needs to be implemented differently in different applications; automotive fieldbuses are functionally different from process plant control fieldbuses.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In June 1999 the IEC's Committee of Action (CA) decided to take a new structure for the fieldbus standards beginning with a first edition valid at the January 1, 2000, in time for the new millennium: There is a large IEC 61158 standard, where all fieldbuses find their place.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The experts have decided that the structure of IEC 61158 is maintained according to different layers, divided into services and protocols.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The individual fieldbuses are incorporated into this structure as different types.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Each part still contains several thousand pages.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Therefore, these parts have been further subdivided into subparts.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The individual protocols have simply been numbered with a type.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Each protocol type thus has its own subpart if required.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In order to find the corresponding subpart of the individual parts of the IEC 61158 standard, one must know the corresponding protocol type for a specific family.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In the 2019 edition of IEC 61158 up to 26 different types of protocols are specified.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In IEC 61158 standardization, the use of brand names is avoided and replaced by dry technical terms and abbreviations.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] For example, Ethernet is replaced by the technically correct CSMA/CD or a reference to the corresponding ISO standard 8802.3.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] This is also the case with fieldbus names, they all are replaced by type numbers.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The reader will therefore never find a designation such as PROFIBUS or DeviceNet in the entire IEC 61158 fieldbus standard.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In the section Compliance to IEC 61784 a complete reference table is provided.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] It is clear that this collection of fieldbus standards in IEC 61158 is not suitable for implementation.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] It must be supplemented with instructions for use.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] These instructions show how and which parts of IEC 61158 can be assembled to a functioning system.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] This assembly instruction has been compiled subsequently as IEC 61784 fieldbus profiles.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The IEC 61784 Part 1 standard with the name *Profile sets for continuous and discrete manufacturing relative to fieldbus use in industrial control systems* lists all fieldbuses which are proposed by the national standardization bodies.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Swiftnet, which is widely used in aircraft construction (Boeing), was included in the first edition of the standard.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] This later proves to be a mistake and in the 2007 edition 2 this protocol was removed from the standard.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] At the same time, the CPF 8 CC-Link, the CPF 9 HART protocol and CPF 16 SERCOS are added.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In the edition 4 in 2014 the last fieldbus CPF 19 MECHATROLINK was included into the standard.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The edition 5 in 2019 was just a maintenance revision without any new profile added.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] See List of automation protocols for fieldbuses that are not included in this standard.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Already in edition 2 of the fieldbus profile first profiles based on Ethernet as physical layer are included.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] All this new developed Real-time Ethernet (RTE) protocols are compiled in IEC 61784 Part 2 as *Additional profiles for ISO/IEC 8802 3 based communication networks in real-time applications*.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The SERCOS solution is interesting in this context.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] This network from the field of axis control had its own standard IEC 61491.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] With the introduction of the Ethernet-based solution SERCOS III, this standard has been taken apart and the communication part is integrated in IEC 61158/61784.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The application part has been integrated together with other drive solutions into a special drive standard IEC 61800-7.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In 2010, a second edition was published to include CPF 17 RAPIEnet and CPF 18 SafetyNET p.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In the third edition (2014), the Industrial Ethernet (IE) version of CC-Link was added.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The two profile families CPF 20 ADS-net and CPF 19 FL-net were added to the fourth edition in 2019.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] For details about these RTEs see the article on Industrial Ethernet.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] For functional safety, different consortia have developed different protocols for safety applications up to Safety Integrity Level 3 (SIL) according to IEC 61508 or Performance Level "e" (PL) according to ISO 13849.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] What most solutions have in common is that they are based on a *Black Channel* and can therefore be transmitted via different fieldbuses and networks.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Depending on the actual profile the safety protocol does provide measures like counters, CRCs, echo, timeout, unique sender and receiver IDs or cross check.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] SERCOS does use the *CIP safety* protocol as well.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In the third edition in 2016 the last safety profile CPF 17 SafetyNET p was added.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] A new edition 4 is expected to be published in 2021.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The standard has now 9 different safety profiles.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] They are all included and referenced in the global compliance table in the next section.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The protocol families of each brand name are called Communication Profile Family and are abbreviated as CPF with a number.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Each protocol family can now define fieldbuses, real-time Ethernet solutions, installation rules and protocols for functional safety.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] These possible profile families are laid down in IEC 61784 and compiled in the following table.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] As an example, we will search for the standards for PROFIBUS-DP.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] This belongs to the CPF 3 family and has the profile CP 3/1.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In Table 5 we find that its protocol scope is defined in IEC 61784 Part 1.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The physical interface is defined in the common 61158-2 under type 3.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The installation regulations can be found in IEC 61784-5-3 in Appendix A.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] It can be combined with the FSCP3/1 as PROFIsafe, which is defined in the IEC 61784-3-3 standard.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] To avoid the manufacturer having to list all these standards explicitly, the reference to the profile is specified in the standard.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Discrete fieldbus networks are often referred to as "device networks".
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Already in the year 2000 the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) decided that a set of *controller-device interfaces* (CDIs) will be specified by the Technical Committee TC 121 *Low-voltage switchgear and controlgear* to cover the device networks.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The amount of cabling required is much lower in fieldbus than in 4–20 mA installations.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] This is because many devices share the same set of cables in a multi-dropped fashion rather than requiring a dedicated set of cables per device as in the case of 4–20 mA devices.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Moreover, several parameters can be communicated per device in a fieldbus network whereas only one parameter can be transmitted on a 4–20 mA connection.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] A fieldbus also provides a good foundation for the creation of a predictive and proactive maintenance strategy.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The diagnostics available from fieldbus devices can be used to address issues with devices before they become critical problems.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Despite each technology sharing the generic name of fieldbus the various fieldbuses are not readily interchangeable.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The differences between them are so profound that they cannot be easily connected to each other.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] To understand the differences among fieldbus standards, it is necessary to understand how fieldbus networks are designed.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] With reference to the OSI model, fieldbus standards are determined by the physical media of the cabling, and layers one, two and seven of the reference model.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] For each technology the physical medium and the physical layer standards fully describe, in detail, the implementation of bit timing, synchronization, encoding/decoding, band rate, bus length and the physical connection of the transceiver to the communication wires.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The data link layer standard is responsible for fully specifying how messages are assembled ready for transmission by the physical layer, error handling, message-filtering and bus arbitration and how these standards are to be implemented in hardware.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] The application layer standard, in general defines how the data communication layers are interfaced to the application that wishes to communicate.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] It describes message specifications, network management implementations and response to the request from the application of services.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Layers three to six are not described in fieldbus standards.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Different fieldbuses offer different sets of features and performance.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] It is difficult to make a general comparison of fieldbus performance because of fundamental differences in data transfer methodology.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] In the comparison table below it is simply noted if the fieldbus in question typically supports data update cycles of 1 millisecond or faster.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] As of 2008, in process control systems, the market is dominated by Foundation Fieldbus and Profibus PA.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Both technologies use the same physical layer (2-wire Manchester-encoded current modulation at 31.25 kHz) but are not interchangeable.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] As a general guide, applications which are controlled and monitored by programmable logic controllers (PLCs) tend towards PROFIBUS, and applications which are controlled and monitored by a digital/distributed control system (DCS) tend towards Foundation Fieldbus.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] PROFIBUS technology is made available through Profibus International with headquarters in Karlsruhe, Germany.
[src:hart-protocol/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus technology is owned and distributed by the Fieldbus Foundation of Austin, Texas.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] The **HART Communication Protocol (Highway Addressable Remote Transducer)** is a hybrid analog+digital industrial automation open protocol.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Its most notable advantage is that it can communicate over legacy 4–20 mA analog instrumentation current loops, sharing the pair of wires used by the analog-only host systems.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] HART is widely used in process and instrumentation systems ranging from small automation applications up to highly sophisticated industrial applications.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Based on the OSI model, HART resides at Layer 7, the Application Layer.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] When sent over 4–20 mA it uses a Bell 202 for layer 1.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] But it is often converted to RS485 or RS232.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] According to Emerson, due to the huge installation base of 4–20 mA systems throughout the world, the HART Protocol is one of the most popular industrial protocols today.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] HART protocol has made a good transition protocol for users who wished to use the legacy 4–20 mA signals, but wanted to implement a "smart" protocol.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] The protocol was developed by Rosemount Inc., built off the Bell 202 early communications standard in the mid-1980s as a proprietary digital communication protocol for their smart field instruments.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Soon it evolved into HART and in 1986 it was made an open protocol.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Since then, the capabilities of the protocol have been enhanced by successive revisions to the specification.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] There are two main operational modes of HART instruments: point-to-point (analog/digital) mode, and multi-drop mode.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] In point-to-point mode the digital signals are overlaid on the 4–20 mA loop current.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Both the 4–20 mA current and the digital signal are valid signalling protocols between the controller and measuring instrument or final control element.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] The polling address of the instrument is set to "0".
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Only one instrument can be put on each instrument cable signal pair.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] One signal, generally specified by the user, is specified to be the 4–20 mA signal.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Other signals are sent digitally on top of the 4–20 mA signal.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] For example, pressure can be sent as 4–20 mA, representing a range of pressures, and temperature can be sent digitally over the same wires.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] In point-to-point mode, the digital part of the HART protocol can be seen as a kind of digital current loop interface.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] In multi-drop mode the analog loop current is fixed at 4 mA and it is possible to have more than one instrument on a signal loop.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] HART revisions 3 through 5 allowed polling addresses of the instruments to be in the range 1–15.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] HART revision 6 allowed addresses 1 to 63; HART revision 7 allows addresses 0 to 63.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Each instrument must have a unique address.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Currently all the newer devices implement five byte preamble, since anything greater reduces the communication speed.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] However, masters are responsible for backwards support.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Master communication to a new device starts with the maximum preamble length (20 bytes) and is later reduced once the preamble size for the current device is determined.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] This byte contains the Master number and specifies that the communication packet is starting.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] normally it set if Expansion field is used, normally 0.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Specifies the destination address as implemented in one of the HART schemes.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] The original addressing scheme used only four bits to specify the device address, which limited the number of devices to 16 including the master.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] The newer scheme utilizes 38 bits to specify the device address.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] This address is requested from the device using either Command 0, or Command 11.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] This is a one byte numerical value representing which command is to be executed.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Command 0 and Command 11 are used to request the device number.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Specifies the number of communication data bytes to follow.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] The status field is absent for the master and is two bytes for the slave.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] This field is used by the slave to inform the master whether it completed the task and what its current health status is.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Data contained in this field depends on the command to be executed.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Checksum is composed of an XOR of all the bytes starting from the start byte and ending with the last byte of the data field, including those bytes.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] Each manufacturer that participates in the HART convention is assigned an identification number.
[src:hart-protocol/highway-addressable-remote-transducer-protocol] This number is communicated as part of the basic device identification command used when first connecting to a device.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Instrumentation can refer to devices as simple as direct-reading thermometers, or as complex as multi-sensor components of industrial control systems.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Instruments can be found in laboratories, refineries, factories and vehicles, as well as in everyday household use (e.g., smoke detectors and thermostats).
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Measuring devices are known as a "meter" and specific types are suffixed "-meter" (such as thermometer, speedometer) in all variants of English.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The history of instrumentation can be divided into several phases.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Elements of industrial instrumentation have long histories.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Scales for comparing weights and simple pointers to indicate position are ancient technologies.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Some of the earliest measurements were of time.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] One of the oldest water clocks was found in the tomb of the ancient Egyptian pharaoh Amenhotep I, buried around 1500 BCE.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Improvements were incorporated in the clocks.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] By 270 BCE they had the rudiments of an automatic control system device.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] In 1663 Christopher Wren presented the Royal Society with a design for a "weather clock".
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] A drawing shows meteorological sensors moving pens over paper driven by clockwork.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Such devices did not become standard in meteorology for two centuries.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The concept has remained virtually unchanged as evidenced by pneumatic chart recorders, where a pressurized bellows displaces a pen.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Integrating sensors, displays, recorders, and controls was uncommon until the industrial revolution, limited by both need and practicality.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Early systems used direct process connections to local control panels for control and indication, which from the early 1930s saw the introduction of pneumatic transmitters and automatic 3-term (PID) controllers.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The ranges of pneumatic transmitters were defined by the need to control valves and actuators in the field.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Typically, a signal ranged from 3 to 15 psi (20 to 100kPa or 0.2 to 1.0 kg/cm2) as a standard, was standardized with 6 to 30 psi occasionally being used for larger valves.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Transistor electronics enabled wiring to replace pipes, initially with a range of 20 to 100mA at up to 90V for loop powered devices, reducing to 4 to 20mA at 12 to 24V in more modern systems.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] A transmitter is a device that produces an output signal, often in the form of a 4–20 mA electrical current signal, although many other options using voltage, frequency, pressure, or ethernet are possible.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The transistor was commercialized by the mid-1950s.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Instruments attached to a control system provided signals used to operate solenoids, valves, regulators, circuit breakers, relays and other devices.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Such devices could control a desired output variable, and provide either remote monitoring or automated control capabilities.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Each instrument company introduced their own standard instrumentation signal, causing confusion until the 4–20 mA range was used as the standard electronic instrument signal for transmitters and valves.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] This signal was eventually standardized as ANSI/ISA S50, "Compatibility of Analog Signals for Electronic Industrial Process Instruments", in the 1970s.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The transformation of instrumentation from mechanical pneumatic transmitters, controllers, and valves to electronic instruments reduced maintenance costs as electronic instruments were more dependable than mechanical instruments.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] This also increased efficiency and production due to their increase in accuracy.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Pneumatics enjoyed some advantages, being favored in corrosive and explosive atmospheres.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] In the early years of process control, process indicators and control elements such as valves were monitored by an operator, that walked around the unit adjusting the valves to obtain the desired temperatures, pressures, and flows.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] As technology evolved pneumatic controllers were invented and mounted in the field that monitored the process and controlled the valves.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] This reduced the amount of time process operators needed to monitor the process.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Latter years, the actual controllers were moved to a central room and signals were sent into the control room to monitor the process and outputs signals were sent to the final control element such as a valve to adjust the process as needed.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] These controllers and indicators were mounted on a wall called a control board.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The operators stood in front of this board walking back and forth monitoring the process indicators.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] This again reduced the number and amount of time process operators were needed to walk around the units.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The most standard pneumatic signal level used during these years was 3–15 psig.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Process control of large industrial plants has evolved through many stages.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Initially, control would be from panels local to the process plant.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] However, this required a large manpower resource to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently staffed central control room.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Effectively this was the centralization of all the localized panels, with the advantages of lower manning levels and easy overview of the process.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Often the controllers were behind the control room panels, and all automatic and manual control outputs were transmitted back to plant.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] However, whilst providing a central control focus, this arrangement was inflexible as each control loop had its own controller hardware, and continual operator movement within the control room was required to view different parts of the process.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] With coming of electronic processors and graphic displays it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] These could be distributed around plant, and communicate with the graphic display in the control room or rooms.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The distributed control concept was born.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The introduction of DCSs and SCADA allowed easy interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] In some cases, the sensor is a very minor element of the mechanism.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Digital cameras and wristwatches might technically meet the loose definition of instrumentation because they record and/or display sensed information.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Under most circumstances neither would be called instrumentation, but when used to measure the elapsed time of a race and to document the winner at the finish line, both would be called instrumentation.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] A very simple example of an instrumentation system is a mechanical thermostat, used to control a household furnace and thus to control room temperature.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] A typical unit senses temperature with a bi-metallic strip.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] It displays temperature by a needle on the free end of the strip.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] It activates the furnace by a mercury switch.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] As the switch is rotated by the strip, the mercury makes physical (and thus electrical) contact between electrodes.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Another example of an instrumentation system is a home security system.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Such a system consists of sensors (motion detection, switches to detect door openings), simple algorithms to detect intrusion, local control (arm/disarm) and remote monitoring of the system so that the police can be summoned.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Communication is an inherent part of the design.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Kitchen appliances use sensors for control.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Modern automobiles have complex instrumentation.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] In addition to displays of engine rotational speed and vehicle linear speed, there are also displays of battery voltage and current, fluid levels, fluid temperatures, distance traveled, and feedback of various controls (turn signals, parking brake, headlights, transmission position).
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Cautions may be displayed for special problems (fuel low, check engine, tire pressure low, door ajar, seat belt unfastened).
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Problems are recorded so they can be reported to diagnostic equipment.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Navigation systems can provide voice commands to reach a destination.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Automotive instrumentation must be cheap and reliable over long periods in harsh environments.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] There may be independent airbag systems that contain sensors, logic and actuators.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Anti-skid braking systems use sensors to control the brakes, while cruise control affects throttle position.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] A wide variety of services can be provided via communication links on the OnStar system.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Autonomous cars (with exotic instrumentation) have been shown.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] "Steam gauges" converted air pressures into needle deflections that could be interpreted as altitude and airspeed.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] A magnetic compass provided a sense of direction.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The displays to the pilot were as critical as the measurements.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] A modern aircraft has a far more sophisticated suite of sensors and displays, which are embedded into avionics systems.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The aircraft may contain inertial navigation systems, global positioning systems, weather radar, autopilots, and aircraft stabilization systems.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Redundant sensors are used for reliability.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] A subset of the information may be transferred to a crash recorder to aid mishap investigations.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Modern pilot displays now include computer displays including head-up displays.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Air traffic control radar is a distributed instrumentation system.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The ground part sends an electromagnetic pulse and receives an echo (at least).
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Aircraft carry transponders that transmit codes on reception of the pulse.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The system displays an aircraft map location, an identifier and optionally altitude.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The map location is based on sensed antenna direction and sensed time delay.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The other information is embedded in the transponder transmission.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Among the possible uses of the term is a collection of laboratory test equipment controlled by a computer through an IEEE-488 bus (also known as GPIB for General Purpose Instrument Bus or HPIB for Hewlitt Packard Instrument Bus).
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Laboratory equipment is available to measure many electrical and chemical quantities.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Such a collection of equipment might be used to automate the testing of drinking water for pollutants.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Instrumentation engineering is loosely defined because the required tasks are very domain dependent.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] An expert in the biomedical instrumentation of laboratory rats has very different concerns than the expert in rocket instrumentation.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Common concerns of both are the selection of appropriate sensors based on size, weight, cost, reliability, accuracy, longevity, environmental robustness, and frequency response.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Some sensors are literally fired in artillery shells.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Others sense thermonuclear explosions until destroyed.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Invariably sensor data must be recorded, transmitted or displayed.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Recording rates and capacities vary enormously.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Transmission can be trivial or can be clandestine, encrypted and low power in the presence of jamming.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Displays can be trivially simple or can require consultation with human factors experts.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Control system design varies from trivial to a separate specialty.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Instrumentation engineers are responsible for integrating the sensors with the recorders, transmitters, displays or control systems, and producing the Piping and instrumentation diagram for the process.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] They may design or specify installation, wiring and signal conditioning.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] They may be responsible for commissioning, calibration, testing and maintenance of the system.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] In a research environment it is common for subject matter experts to have substantial instrumentation system expertise.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] An astronomer knows the structure of the universe and a great deal about telescopes – optics, pointing and cameras (or other sensing elements).
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] That often includes the hard-won knowledge of the operational procedures that provide the best results.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] For example, an astronomer is often knowledgeable of techniques to minimize temperature gradients that cause air turbulence within the telescope.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Instrumentation technologists, technicians and mechanics specialize in troubleshooting, repairing and maintaining instruments and instrumentation systems.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Ralph Müller (1940) stated, "That the history of physical science is largely the history of instruments and their intelligent use is well known.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The broad generalizations and theories which have arisen from time to time have stood or fallen on the basis of accurate measurement, and in several instances new instruments have had to be devised for the purpose.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] There is little evidence to show that the mind of modern man is superior to that of the ancients.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Davis Baird has argued that the major change associated with Floris Cohen's identification of a "fourth big scientific revolution" or more often known as Fourth Industrial Revolution after World War II is the development of scientific instrumentation, not only in chemistry but across the sciences.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] In chemistry, the introduction of new instrumentation in the 1940s was "nothing less than a scientific and technological revolution" in which classical wet-and-dry methods of structural organic chemistry were discarded, and new areas of research opened up.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] Wildhack discussed both the productive and destructive potential inherent in process control.
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] The ability to make precise, verifiable and reproducible measurements of the natural world, at levels that were not previously observable, using scientific instrumentation, has "provided a different texture of the world".
[src:hart-protocol/instrumentation] This instrumentation revolution fundamentally changes human abilities to monitor and respond, as is illustrated in the examples of DDT monitoring and the use of UV spectrophotometry and gas chromatography to monitor water pollutants.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] In IPC, control theory provides the theoretical framework to understand system dynamics, predict outcomes and design control strategies to ensure predetermined objectives, utilizing concepts like feedback loops, stability analysis and controller design.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] On the other hand, the physical apparatus of IPC, based on automation technologies, consists of several components.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Firstly, a network of sensors continuously measure various process variables (such as temperature, pressure, etc.) and product quality variables.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] This creates a continuous closed-loop cycle of measurement, comparison, control action, and re-evaluation which guarantees that the process remains within established parameters.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The HMI (Human-Machine Interface) acts as the "control panel" for the IPC system where small number of human operators can monitor the process and make informed decisions regarding adjustments.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] IPCs can range from controlling the temperature and level of a single process vessel (controlled environment tank for mixing, separating, reacting, or storing materials in industrial processes.) to a complete chemical processing plant with several thousand control feedback loops.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] IPC provides several critical benefits to manufacturing companies.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] By maintaining a tight control over key process variables, it helps reduce energy use, minimize waste and shorten downtime for peak efficiency and reduced costs.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] It ensures consistent and improved product quality with little variability, which satisfies the customers and strengthens the company's reputation.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] It improves safety by detecting and alerting human operators about potential issues early, thus preventing accidents, equipment failures, process disruptions and costly downtime.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Analyzing trends and behaviors in the vast amounts of data collected real-time helps engineers identify areas of improvement, refine control strategies and continuously enhance production efficiency using a data-driven approach.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] IPC is used across a wide range of industries where precise control is important.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The applications can range from controlling the temperature and level of a single process vessel, to a complete chemical processing plant with several thousand control loops.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] In automotive manufacturing, IPC ensures consistent quality by meticulously controlling processes like welding and painting.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Mining operations are optimized with IPC monitoring ore crushing and adjusting conveyor belt speeds for maximum output.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Dredging benefits from precise control of suction pressure, dredging depth and sediment discharge rate by IPC, ensuring efficient and sustainable practices.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Pulp and paper production leverages IPC to regulate chemical processes (e.g., pH and bleach concentration) and automate paper machine operations to control paper sheet moisture content and drying temperature for consistent quality.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] In chemical plants, it ensures the safe and efficient production of chemicals by controlling temperature, pressure and reaction rates.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Oil refineries use it to smoothly convert crude oil into gasoline and other petroleum products.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] In power plants, it helps maintain stable operating conditions necessary for a continuous electricity supply.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] In food and beverage production, it helps ensure consistent texture, safety and quality.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Pharmaceutical companies relies on it to produce life-saving drugs safely and effectively.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The development of large industrial process control systems has been instrumental in enabling the design of large high volume and complex processes, which could not be otherwise economically or safely operated.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Early process control breakthroughs came most frequently in the form of water control devices.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Ktesibios of Alexandria is credited for inventing float valves to regulate water level of water clocks in the 3rd century BC.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] In the 1st century AD, Heron of Alexandria invented a water valve similar to the fill valve used in modern toilets.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Later process controls inventions involved basic physics principles.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] In 1620, Cornelis Drebbel invented a bimetallic thermostat for controlling the temperature in a furnace.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] In 1681, Denis Papin discovered the pressure inside a vessel could be regulated by placing weights on top of the vessel lid.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] In 1745, Edmund Lee created the fantail to improve windmill efficiency; a fantail was a smaller windmill placed 90° of the larger fans to keep the face of the windmill pointed directly into the oncoming wind.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] With the dawn of the Industrial Revolution in the 1760s, process controls inventions were aimed to replace human operators with mechanized processes.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] In 1784, Oliver Evans created a water-powered flourmill which operated using buckets and screw conveyors.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Henry Ford applied the same theory in 1910 when the assembly line was created to decrease human intervention in the automobile production process.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] For continuously variable process control it was not until 1922 that a formal control law for what we now call PID control or three-term control was first developed using theoretical analysis, by Russian American engineer Nicolas Minorsky.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Minorsky was researching and designing automatic ship steering for the US Navy and based his analysis on observations of a helmsman.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] He noted the helmsman steered the ship based not only on the current course error, but also on past error, as well as the current rate of change; this was then given a mathematical treatment by Minorsky.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] His goal was stability, not general control, which simplified the problem significantly.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] While proportional control provided stability against small disturbances, it was insufficient for dealing with a steady disturbance, notably a stiff gale (due to steady-state error), which required adding the integral term.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Finally, the derivative term was added to improve stability and control.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] However this required a large manpower resource to attend to these dispersed panels, and there was no overall view of the process.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The next logical development was the transmission of all plant measurements to a permanently-staffed central control room.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Effectively this was the centralization of all the localized panels, with the advantages of lower manning levels and easier overview of the process.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] With the coming of electronic processors and graphic displays it became possible to replace these discrete controllers with computer-based algorithms, hosted on a network of input/output racks with their own control processors.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] These could be distributed around the plant, and communicate with the graphic display in the control room or rooms.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The distributed control system (DCS) was born.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The introduction of DCSs allowed easy interconnection and re-configuration of plant controls such as cascaded loops and interlocks, and easy interfacing with other production computer systems.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The accompanying diagram is a general model which shows functional manufacturing levels in a large process using processor and computer-based control.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] To determine the fundamental model for any process, the inputs and outputs of the system are defined differently than for other chemical processes.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The balance equations are defined by the control inputs and outputs rather than the material inputs.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The control model is a set of equations used to predict the behavior of a system and can help determine what the response to change will be.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The state variable (x) is a measurable variable that is a good indicator of the state of the system, such as temperature (energy balance), volume (mass balance) or concentration (component balance).
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Input variable (u) is a specified variable that commonly include flow rates.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The entering and exiting flows are both considered control inputs.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The control input can be classified as a manipulated, disturbance, or unmonitored variable.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Parameters (p) are usually a physical limitation and something that is fixed for the system, such as the vessel volume or the viscosity of the material.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Output (y) is the metric used to determine the behavior of the system.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The control output can be classified as measured, unmeasured, or unmonitored.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Processes can be characterized as batch, continuous, or hybrid.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Batch applications require that specific quantities of raw materials be combined in specific ways for particular duration to produce an intermediate or end result.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] One example is the production of adhesives and glues, which normally require the mixing of raw materials in a heated vessel for a period of time to form a quantity of end product.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Other important examples are the production of food, beverages and medicine.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Batch processes are generally used to produce a relatively low to intermediate quantity of product per year (a few pounds to millions of pounds).
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] A continuous physical system is represented through variables that are smooth and uninterrupted in time.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The control of the water temperature in a heating jacket, for example, is an example of continuous process control.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Some important continuous processes are the production of fuels, chemicals and plastics.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Continuous processes in manufacturing are used to produce very large quantities of product per year (millions to billions of pounds).
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Such controls use feedback such as in the PID controller A PID Controller includes proportional, integrating, and derivative controller functions.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Applications having elements of batch and continuous process control are often called hybrid applications.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The fundamental building block of any industrial control system is the control loop, which controls just one process variable.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] An example is shown in the accompanying diagram, where the flow rate in a pipe is controlled by a PID controller, assisted by what is effectively a cascaded loop in the form of a valve servo-controller to ensure correct valve positioning.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Some large systems may have several hundreds or thousands of control loops.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] In complex processes the loops are interactive, so that the operation of one loop may affect the operation of another.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The system diagram for representing control loops is a Piping and instrumentation diagram.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Commonly used control systems include programmable logic controller (PLC), Distributed Control System (DCS) or SCADA.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] If a control valve were used to hold level in a tank, the level controller would compare the equivalent reading of a level sensor to the level setpoint and determine whether more or less valve opening was necessary to keep the level constant.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] A cascaded flow controller could then calculate the change in the valve position.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The economic nature of many products manufactured in batch and continuous processes require highly efficient operation due to thin margins.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The competing factor in process control is that products must meet certain specifications in order to be satisfactory.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] These specifications can come in two forms: a minimum and maximum for a property of the material or product, or a range within which the property must be.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] All loops are susceptible to disturbances and therefore a buffer must be used on process set points to ensure disturbances do not cause the material or product to go out of specifications.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] This buffer comes at an economic cost (i.e. additional processing, maintaining elevated or depressed process conditions, etc.).
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Process efficiency can be enhanced by reducing the margins necessary to ensure product specifications are met.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] This can be done by improving the control of the process to minimize the effect of disturbances on the process.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] The efficiency is improved in a two step method of narrowing the variance and shifting the target.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Margins can be narrowed through various process upgrades (i.e. equipment upgrades, enhanced control methods, etc.).
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Once margins are narrowed, an economic analysis can be done on the process to determine how the set point target is to be shifted.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Less conservative process set points lead to increased economic efficiency.
[src:hart-protocol/process-control] Effective process control strategies increase the competitive advantage of manufacturers who employ them.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] In electronics and telecommunications, a **radio transmitter** or just **transmitter** (often abbreviated as **XMTR** or **TX** in technical documents) is an electronic device which produces radio waves with an antenna with the purpose of signal transmission to a radio receiver.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The transmitter itself generates a radio frequency alternating current, which is applied to the antenna.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] When excited by this alternating current, the antenna radiates radio waves.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The term *transmitter* is usually limited to equipment that generates radio waves for communication purposes; or radiolocation, such as radar and navigational transmitters.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Generators of radio waves for heating or industrial purposes, such as microwave ovens or diathermy equipment, are not usually called transmitters, even though they often have similar circuits.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The term is popularly used more specifically to refer to a broadcast transmitter, a transmitter used in broadcasting, as in *FM radio transmitter* or television transmitter.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] This usage typically includes both the transmitter proper, the antenna, and often the building it is housed in.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] A transmitter can be a **separate group** among all pieces of electronic equipments, or an electrical circuit within another electronic device.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] A transmitter and a receiver combined in one unit is called a transceiver.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The purpose of most transmitters is radio communication of information over a distance.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The information is provided to the transmitter in the form of an electronic signal called the modulation signal, such as an audio (sound) signal from a microphone, a video (TV) signal from a video camera, or in wireless networking devices, a digital signal from a computer.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The transmitter generates a radio frequency signal which when applied to the antenna produces the radio waves, called the carrier signal.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] It combines the carrier with the modulation signal, a process called modulation.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The information can be added to the carrier in several different ways, in different types of transmitters.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] In an amplitude modulation (AM) transmitter, the information is added to the radio signal by varying its amplitude.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] In a frequency modulation (FM) transmitter, it is added by varying the radio signal's frequency slightly.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Many other types of modulation are also used.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The radio signal from the transmitter is applied to the antenna, which radiates the energy as radio waves.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The antenna may be enclosed inside the case or attached to the outside of the transmitter, as in portable devices such as cell phones, walkie-talkies, and garage door openers.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] In more powerful transmitters, the antenna may be located on top of a building or on a separate tower, and connected to the transmitter by a feed line, that is a transmission line.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] A cellphone has several transmitters: a duplex cell transceiver, a Wi-Fi modem, and a Bluetooth modem.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] contain low power 2.4 GHz radio transmitters to communicate with each other.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] control contains a low-power 2.4 GHz transmitter that sends coded commands to the garage door mechanism to open or close.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] (background) which connects it to the Internet, creating a home Wi-Fi network.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Electromagnetic waves are radiated by electric charges when they are accelerated.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Radio waves, electromagnetic waves of radio frequency, are generated by time-varying electric currents, consisting of electrons flowing through a metal conductor called an antenna which are changing their velocity and thus accelerating.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] An alternating current flowing back and forth in an antenna will create an oscillating magnetic field around the conductor.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The alternating voltage will also charge the ends of the conductor alternately positive and negative, creating an oscillating electric field around the conductor.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] If the frequency of the oscillations is high enough, in the radio frequency range above about 20 kHz, the oscillating coupled electric and magnetic fields will radiate away from the antenna into space as an electromagnetic wave, a radio wave.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] A radio transmitter is an electronic circuit which transforms electric power from a power source, a battery or mains power, into a radio frequency alternating current to apply to the antenna, and the antenna radiates the energy from this current as radio waves.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The transmitter also encodes information such as an audio or video signal into the radio frequency current to be carried by the radio waves.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] When they strike the antenna of a radio receiver, the waves excite similar (but less powerful) radio frequency currents in it.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The radio receiver extracts the information from the received waves.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] In higher frequency transmitters, in the UHF and microwave range, free running oscillators are unstable at the output frequency.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Older designs used an oscillator at a lower frequency, which was multiplied by frequency multipliers to get a signal at the desired frequency.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Modern designs more commonly use an oscillator at the operating frequency which is stabilized by phase locking to a very stable lower frequency reference, usually a crystal oscillator.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Two radio transmitters in the same area that attempt to transmit on the same frequency will interfere with each other, causing garbled reception, so neither transmission may be received clearly.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Interference with radio transmissions can not only have a large economic cost, it can be life-threatening (for example, in the case of interference with emergency communications or air traffic control).
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] For this reason, in most countries, use of transmitters is strictly controlled by law.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Transmitters must be licensed by governments, under a variety of license classes depending on use such as broadcast, marine radio, Airband, Amateur and are restricted to certain frequencies and power levels.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] A body called the International Telecommunication Union (ITU) allocates the frequency bands in the radio spectrum to various classes of users.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] In some classes, each transmitter is given a unique call sign consisting of a string of letters and numbers which must be used as an identifier in transmissions.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The operator of the transmitter usually must hold a government license, such as a general radiotelephone operator license, which is obtained by passing a test demonstrating adequate technical and legal knowledge of safe radio operation.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Exceptions to the above regulations allow the unlicensed use of low-power short-range transmitters in consumer products such as cell phones, cordless telephones, wireless microphones, walkie-talkies, Wi-Fi and Bluetooth devices, garage door openers, and baby monitors.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] In the US, these fall under Part 15 of the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) regulations.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Although they can be operated without a license, these devices still generally must be type-approved before sale.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The first primitive radio transmitters (called spark gap transmitters) were built by German physicist Heinrich Hertz in 1887 during his pioneering investigations of radio waves.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] These generated radio waves by a high voltage spark between two conductors.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Beginning in 1895, Guglielmo Marconi developed the first practical radio communication systems using these transmitters, and radio began to be used commercially around 1900.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Spark transmitters could not transmit audio (sound) and instead transmitted information by radiotelegraphy: the operator tapped on a telegraph key which turned the transmitter on-and-off to produce radio wave pulses spelling out text messages in telegraphic code, usually Morse code.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] At the receiver, these pulses were sometimes directly recorded on paper tapes, but more common was audible reception.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The pulses were audible as beeps in the receiver's earphones, which were translated back to text by an operator who knew Morse code.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] These spark-gap transmitters were used during the first three decades of radio (1887–1917), called the wireless telegraphy or "spark" era.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Because they generated damped waves, spark transmitters were electrically "noisy".
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Their energy was spread over a broad band of frequencies, creating radio noise which interfered with other transmitters.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Damped wave emissions were banned by international law in 1934.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Two short-lived competing transmitter technologies came into use after the turn of the century, which were the first continuous wave transmitters: the arc converter (Poulsen arc) in 1904 and the Alexanderson alternator around 1910, which were used into the 1920s.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] All these early technologies were replaced by vacuum tube transmitters in the 1920s, which used the feedback oscillator invented by Edwin Armstrong and Alexander Meissner around 1912, based on the Audion (triode) vacuum tube invented by Lee De Forest in 1906.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Vacuum tube transmitters were inexpensive and produced continuous waves, and could be easily modulated to transmit audio (sound) using amplitude modulation (AM).
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] This made AM radio broadcasting possible, which began in about 1920.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Practical frequency modulation (FM) transmission was invented by Edwin Armstrong in 1933, who showed that it was less vulnerable to noise and static than AM.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The first FM radio station was licensed in 1937.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Experimental television transmission had been conducted by radio stations since the late 1920s, but practical television broadcasting didn't begin until the late 1930s.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The development of radar during World War II motivated the evolution of high frequency transmitters in the UHF and microwave ranges, using new active devices such as the magnetron, klystron, and traveling wave tube.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The invention of the transistor allowed the development in the 1960s of small portable transmitters such as wireless microphones, garage door openers and walkie-talkies.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] The need to conserve bandwidth in the increasingly congested radio spectrum is driving the development of new types of transmitters such as spread spectrum, trunked radio systems and cognitive radio.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] A related trend has been an ongoing transition from analog to digital radio transmission methods.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Digital modulation can have greater spectral efficiency than analog modulation; that is it can often transmit more information (data rate) in a given bandwidth than analog, using data compression algorithms.
[src:hart-protocol/transmitter] Other advantages of digital transmission are increased noise immunity, and greater flexibility and processing power of digital signal processing integrated circuits.
